\f1\b 2. Browser Automation (Playwright MCP Already Exists)
\f0\b0 \
\
    
\f1\b What exists now:
\f0\b0  Playwright MCP is registered in featured_mcp_servers.json as "Playwright Browser" \'97 agents can navigate\
    websites, click elements, fill forms, take screenshots, extract accessibility trees. It's already documented as usable for\
    "competitor analysis, usability testing, design evaluation, and web content extraction."\
\
    
\f1\b What AgentScope has:
\f0\b0  BrowserUseAgent \'97 a dedicated agent type for web navigation\
\
    
\f1\b How to improve in Istara's approach:
\f0\b0 \
     - The Playwright MCP is there but it's 
\f1\b passive
\f0\b0  \'97 you have to manually connect it\
     - Create a 
\f1\b dedicated Browser Skill
\f0\b0  that wraps Playwright MCP into structured UX research workflows:\
       - "Competitive Analysis" skill: navigate to competitor URLs, screenshot pages, extract UX patterns\
       - "Accessibility Audit" skill: navigate to a URL, run accessibility tree analysis, flag WCAG violations\
       - "Heuristic Evaluation" skill: systematically test a live site against Nielsen's heuristics\
     - The skill would use Playwright MCP as a tool but add the methodology layer that Istara does best\
\
    
\f1\b Why this fits Istara:
\f0\b0  It's exactly the pattern \'97 take a raw tool (Playwright MCP) and wrap it in research methodology (the\
    skill). The agent doesn't just browse \'97 it evaluates against established frameworks.\
\
